Learning objectives
By the end of this chapter, you should be able to:

explain why openness and reproducibility are now core expectations in research;
distinguish between open research, transparency and reproducibility;
recognise common sources of irreproducibility in everyday workflows;
understand how open practices can reduce risk, inefficiency and avoidable error.

This chapter is deliberately conceptual. Later chapters turn these ideas into practical steps: project organisation, data management planning, documentation, code quality, automation, publishing, persistent identifiers and reuse.

Minimum expectations in practice
Open research is increasingly treated as a default position, applied across the research lifecycle and implemented proportionately within ethical, legal and contractual constraints.
In most UCL and UK-funded research contexts, you should assume that the following expectations may apply somewhere in your project:

plan data management proportionately, and document decisions;
make outputs findable and preservable, including data, code, protocols, materials or metadata where appropriate;
enable open access to publications through institutional and funder-compliant routes;
record constraints explicitly, including sensitive data, governance restrictions, intellectual property or contractual limits;
document how restrictions affect sharing, access, reuse and retention.

The key point is proportionality. Open research does not mean treating all projects in the same way. It means making defensible decisions and recording them clearly.






Open does not always mean public



For sensitive data, good open research may mean clear metadata, documented access routes, transparent governance, synthetic examples, preserved code and well-described restrictions.

Open research in day-to-day work
Open research is not only about making outputs publicly available at the end of a project. Across the research lifecycle, work should be organised, documented and described so that others — including your future self — can understand:

what was done;
why it was done;
how results were produced;
what assumptions and decisions shaped the work;
what could and could not be reused;
what restrictions apply.

Three foundations support this.


Documentation
READMEs, protocols, decision logs, metadata, data dictionaries and codebooks that capture context and rationale.


Organisation
Consistent folder structures, file names and versioning that reduce ambiguity and error.


Description
Clear metadata and access information so that outputs are interpretable, discoverable and reusable where appropriate.


These foundations are particularly important for collaborative, longitudinal or sensitive-data projects, where people may join or leave the team and not all materials can be made publicly available.

AI and reproducibility
Automated and AI-assisted tools can support research workflows, for example by helping with coding, summarising, drafting, checking or exploring ideas. They can also introduce reproducibility challenges.
These include:

outputs that vary across prompts, sessions or model versions;
unclear provenance of generated text, code or summaries;
hidden assumptions in suggested analyses;
difficulty reconstructing how an output was produced;
risk of over-reliance on plausible but incorrect outputs.

The same reproducibility principles still apply: document important decisions, keep records of prompts or generated code where relevant, check outputs critically, and make clear where AI-assisted tools have materially shaped the work.

What comes next?
Later chapters translate these ideas into practical steps:

describing outputs using FAIR principles (Chapter 2: FAIR basics);
organising projects so work remains legible and maintainable;
documenting decisions and workflows so results can be understood and defended;
improving code quality and reducing manual steps where appropriate;
preparing outputs for sharing, archiving, attribution and reuse.

You are not expected to change everything at once. The workshop is designed to support incremental improvement: making each project a little easier to understand, check and build on.

Learning objectives
By the end of this chapter, you should be able to:

explain what the FAIR principles are and why they matter;
distinguish FAIR from openness, documentation and data management planning;
describe what Findable, Accessible, Interoperable and Reusable mean in practice;
recognise how FAIR applies to data, code, protocols, documentation and workflows;
explain why accessibility does not necessarily mean public openness;
identify practical steps that make research outputs more FAIR;
understand how FAIR connects to data integrity principles such as ALCOA.

This chapter builds on Chapter 1 — Why Open Research and Reproducibility?. Chapter 1 introduced the problem: research can become difficult to understand, check or reuse when decisions, files, code and outputs are poorly documented. FAIR gives us a language for designing outputs so they remain useful beyond the immediate project.

Findable
Findable means that research outputs can be discovered by others, including people outside the original project.
Findability is supported by:

a clear title and description;
persistent identifiers such as DOIs;
author identifiers such as ORCID iDs;
keywords and subject terms;
repository records or catalogue entries;
metadata that can be indexed by search systems;
file names and folder structures that make sense beyond the original analyst.

Findability is not the same as access. A restricted dataset can still be findable if there is a public metadata record explaining what the dataset contains and how access can be requested.






Practical example



A dataset stored only on a personal laptop is not findable.
A dataset deposited in a trusted repository with a DOI, metadata, authorship, dates, access conditions and a citation format is much more findable — even if access to the data is restricted.

Accessible
Accessible means that it is clear how an output can be accessed, under what conditions, and by whom.
Access may be:

open, where the output can be downloaded directly;
mediated, where users must complete a request or registration process;
controlled, where access depends on approvals, contracts, information governance or safe settings;
closed, where access is not possible, but the reason is documented.

Accessible outputs should state:

who can access the material;
where the material is held;
whether access is open, restricted, embargoed or unavailable;
what conditions apply;
who to contact or what process to follow;
whether metadata remain available if the data are withdrawn or restricted.

For sensitive data, accessibility is often about making the access route and restrictions transparent, not about removing safeguards.

Interoperable
Interoperable means that outputs can be understood and used correctly in different contexts, systems or tools.
Interoperability is supported by:

open or widely used file formats;
machine-readable formats where appropriate;
consistent variable names and coding;
clear units, dates, spatial references and classifications;
standard vocabularies, ontologies or metadata schemas where relevant;
documentation of transformations, exclusions and derived variables;
avoiding unnecessary proprietary formats when possible.

In practice, interoperability reduces friction. It helps prevent situations where a file technically exists but cannot be interpreted, combined, imported, or used correctly by another person or software environment.

Reusable
Reusable means that outputs can be used again for future research, whether by others or by your future self.
Reusability depends on context. A file is not reusable simply because it exists. It needs enough information for someone to judge whether it is appropriate, valid and permitted to use.
Reusable outputs usually include:

a README or equivalent orientation document;
metadata and data dictionaries;
information about provenance and version history;
information about software, code or dependencies;
a licence or reuse statement;
known limitations and constraints;
citation information;
contact or access information where appropriate.







Reuse is responsible reuse



FAIR does not mean encouraging inappropriate reuse. It means providing enough information for someone to understand what reuse is possible, what conditions apply, and what limitations should be respected.

FAIR and sensitive or restricted data
FAIR is particularly useful when data cannot be made openly available, because it helps separate description from access.
For sensitive or restricted data, you may still be able to make the following FAIR:

metadata describing the dataset;
a data dictionary or variable list;
information about data provenance;
the protocol or analysis plan;
synthetic or dummy example data;
code that can be run in the approved environment;
information about governance and access routes;
a data access statement in the publication;
restrictions, retention rules and destruction plans.

The key is to record the constraint explicitly. A statement such as “data are unavailable” is rarely sufficient. A better statement explains what exists, why it cannot be openly shared, what access may be possible, and who controls access.

Short exercise: “as open as possible, as closed as necessary”
Choose one research output from your own work.
Ask:

Could this output be shared openly?
If not, what exactly prevents sharing?
Could the metadata, code, protocol, synthetic example or access statement still be shared?
Where should this decision be recorded?

What comes next?
FAIR and ALCOA provide the principles. The next chapters move into implementation.
Later chapters cover:

project organisation and continuity;
data management planning;
file naming, folder structures and tidy data;
documentation, README files, metadata, ELNs and SOPs;
code quality, testing and automation;
publishing, persistent identifiers and preparing for reuse.

You are not expected to solve everything in this chapter. The aim is to recognise the principles and start applying them proportionately.

Learning objectives
By the end of this chapter, you should be able to:

explain why project organisation is central to reproducibility and continuity;
distinguish between a project folder and a well-organised project;
choose a folder structure that reflects the work being done;
separate raw, derived and output files in a way that protects provenance;
apply file naming conventions that make meaning and version history visible;
use simple versioning practices without turning the workshop into a Git course;
identify what belongs in the project README and what belongs in a later DMP, data dictionary or decision log.

This chapter builds on Chapter 2: FAIR basics. The next chapter, Chapter 4: Data Management Plans, explains how data-management decisions, responsibilities and constraints are formally recorded.

Why project organisation matters
Many reproducibility problems are structural rather than technical. They arise because files are scattered across drives, raw and cleaned data are mixed, outputs are overwritten, or important decisions are hidden in email, Teams messages or personal notebooks.
These problems usually feel small at the time. They become serious later: during analysis, handover, peer review, audit, publication, archiving or reuse. The CESSDA Data Management Expert Guide emphasises file organisation and documentation as practical foundations for data management and reuse1,2. Similar principles are used in reproducible computational project guidance, including Noble’s project organisation recommendations and the TIER protocol3,4.
Good project organisation helps others understand:

what the project is for;
what data, code, documents and outputs exist;
which files are raw, derived, interim or final;
where the current version is;
what can be re-run and what is only an output;
where conventions and decisions are documented;
which materials are safe to edit and which should be preserved.

The point is not administrative tidiness for its own sake. Organisation reduces ambiguity. Ambiguity is where duplicated work, avoidable error and loss of project memory often begin.






A simple test



If someone joined your project tomorrow, could they understand the purpose of the project, the main folders, the current version of key files, and where to start within ten minutes?
If not, the project may need a clearer structure, a README, or a simpler naming and versioning convention.

Versioning without making this a Git workshop
Version control means keeping track of changes so that earlier states can be recovered and current work can be understood. For code, Git is the most powerful and widely used tool. However, not every participant needs a full Git workflow before they can improve reproducibility.
For this workshop, start with proportionate versioning:

do not overwrite raw data;
use stable file names for scripts and outputs;
use dates and version numbers consistently where needed;
keep a changelog for meaningful updates;
use numbered scripts to make workflow order visible;
keep old versions only where they are meaningful;
avoid parallel personal versions such as analysis_Jo.R, analysis_Matt_edits.R, analysis_new.R.


When a filename version is enough
Filename versioning may be sufficient for:

draft reports;
circulated manuscripts;
frozen data extracts;
external files received from collaborators;
teaching materials or workshop drafts.



When you need a changelog
A changelog is useful when changes affect interpretation, reproducibility or reuse. Examples include:

updating the data extract;
changing inclusion/exclusion criteria;
changing an exposure definition;
changing an analysis model;
correcting an error;
changing a file format;
preparing a release for archiving.

A simple changelog can be a table:










Date
File or component
Change
Reason
Who




2026-03-10
02_clean.R
Added postcode validation step
Missing postcodes were not being flagged
JC


2026-03-14
data/processed/
Recreated cleaned dataset
Updated raw extract received
JC


2026-03-18
outputs/tables/
Regenerated Table 1
Categories corrected after review
JC





When Git becomes useful
Git becomes particularly useful when:

multiple people edit code;
the project includes many scripts;
you need to compare changes over time;
you want to publish code with a DOI later;
you want a robust record of analytical development.

Git and GitHub are introduced later in relation to code quality and release. Here, the key principle is simpler: changes should be visible and recoverable.






Versioning principle



You should be able to answer: what changed, when, why, and where is the previous version if we need it?

Decisions should not live only in email
Email and chat messages are useful for discussion but poor places to store the project record. Decisions become hard to find, people are left out of threads, and the reasoning behind analytical choices may be lost.
A project should have a visible place for decisions that affect interpretation or reproducibility. This may be a decision log, analysis log, lab notebook, issue tracker, or structured document.
Examples of decisions worth recording include:

changing inclusion or exclusion rules;
choosing between alternative exposure metrics;
changing a variable definition;
excluding records because of data quality concerns;
using a restricted dataset under specific governance conditions;
deciding what can be shared and what must remain restricted;
changing software or package versions where it affects results.

Decision logs are covered in more detail in the documentation chapter. In this chapter, the important point is that the project structure should include somewhere for decisions to go.

Learning objectives
By the end of this chapter, you should be able to:

explain the purpose of a DMP beyond compliance;
recognise a DMP as a living record of decisions;
identify the main areas a DMP should cover;
distinguish data description, data organisation and data governance;
record roles and responsibilities in a way that supports accountability;
explain how DMPs support FAIR, responsible sharing and later reuse;
locate UCL and external resources for drafting or reviewing a DMP.

This chapter builds on Chapter 2: FAIR basics and Chapter 3: Project organisation and continuity. Chapter 5 then moves to the internal structure and quality of data files.

What is a DMP?
A Data Management Plan records how research data and related materials will be managed during and after a project. It usually covers what data will be collected or reused, how they will be stored and protected, how they will be documented, what will be shared or archived, what restrictions apply, and who is responsible.
A DMP is not a promise that nothing will change. It is a record of the best current plan, with enough detail to show that data management has been thought through. A strong DMP is updated when the project changes.






A DMP records decisions



A useful DMP should answer:

what data will be collected, created or reused;
how data will be organised, stored and protected;
who is responsible for key decisions and tasks;
what will be shared, archived or restricted;
why restrictions apply;
under what conditions data, metadata, code or documentation can be accessed.

Why DMPs matter
DMPs are often introduced as funder or institutional requirements, but their practical value is broader. A good DMP helps a team avoid late-stage uncertainty about storage, access, sharing, retention, responsibilities and costs.
DMPs are useful because they:

make data-related decisions explicit;
support ethical and legal compliance;
reduce ambiguity about access and responsibilities;
make FAIR planning more concrete;
help identify what needs to be documented or archived;
support handover when staff, students or collaborators change;
reduce last-minute work at publication or project close;
provide evidence that risks and restrictions have been considered.

DMPonline provides a widely used platform for creating, reviewing and sharing DMPs that align with institutional and funder expectations1. The Digital Curation Centre also provides guidance and examples across research contexts2.

A DMP is a living document
A weak DMP is written once and then forgotten. A useful DMP is revisited as the project develops.
The plan may need updating when:

a new data source is added;
data volume, format or sensitivity changes;
access conditions change;
new collaborators join;
a student or staff member leaves;
ethics, governance or contractual approvals change;
derived datasets or outputs become important;
analysis moves from exploratory to final;
the project prepares for publication, archiving or closure.







Updating a DMP is good practice



Changing a DMP is not a failure. It is evidence that the plan is being used as a working document rather than a static compliance exercise.

What a DMP should usually cover
Different templates vary, but most DMPs cover the same broad areas. UCL’s research data management guidance and DMP template provide local support for these issues3–5. External guidance from the UK Data Service, Oxford, ELIXIR and ARDC can also help interpret what good answers look like in practice6–9.

1. Data collection or reuse
Describe what data will be collected, created or reused.
Include:

type of data, such as survey data, interviews, sensor data, administrative data, geospatial data, code, images or derived measures;
approximate scale, such as number of participants, files, records, variables or expected storage size;
whether the data are new, reused, purchased, linked or obtained from a partner;
whether the data contain personal, sensitive, confidential or commercially restricted information;
what permissions, approvals or agreements are needed.

For secondary data or linked administrative data, the DMP should make clear who owns or controls access to the source data and what restrictions apply.


2. Storage and security
Describe where data will be stored during the project and how access will be controlled.
Include:

approved storage locations;
backup arrangements;
access controls and permissions;
encryption or secure transfer where needed;
whether data will be held in a trusted research environment or secure setting;
who can access identifiable, sensitive or restricted data;
what happens when staff or students leave the project.

Avoid vague statements such as “data will be stored securely” unless you specify where, how and by whom.


3. Organisation and documentation
Describe how the data and related materials will be organised and documented.
Include:

where project conventions are documented;
what README files, data dictionaries, codebooks or metadata will be created;
how raw, derived and final data will be distinguished;
how versions and changes will be tracked;
how software, code or workflow dependencies will be recorded;
what documentation is needed for reuse or handover.

The details of folder structure and file naming are covered in Chapter 3. In the DMP, the key point is to record that conventions exist and where they can be found.


4. Ethics, governance and legal constraints
Describe the ethical, legal and contractual conditions that shape data management.
Include:

ethics approvals;
consent conditions;
data-sharing or data-processing agreements;
information governance requirements;
data protection considerations;
intellectual property or commercial restrictions;
partner or funder conditions;
limits on international transfer or external access.

This is especially important for projects using personal data, NHS data, administrative records, schools data, environmental data linked to individuals, or commercially provided datasets.


5. Sharing, access and archiving
Describe what will happen to data and related outputs at the end of the project.
Include:

what data, code, metadata, documentation or materials will be shared;
what cannot be shared and why;
where outputs will be archived or deposited;
whether a repository can issue a persistent identifier;
what access conditions will apply;
what licence will be used where appropriate;
what will be retained internally and for how long.

A good DMP distinguishes between open access, controlled access, restricted access, and metadata-only records. Sensitive or restricted data may still have public metadata, a data access statement, preserved code, synthetic examples or clear access conditions.


6. Roles and responsibilities
Describe who is responsible for key data management tasks and who has authority to make decisions.
This should cover responsibility across the lifecycle: data collection or receipt, storage, cleaning, documentation, analysis, sharing, archiving and project closure.
A DMP should not leave responsibility implicit. If responsibility is unclear, tasks tend to be missed or assumed to belong to someone else.

Sensitive, restricted and high-risk data
Some projects require more detailed planning because the risk is higher. Examples include:

personal or identifiable data;
linked administrative data;
health, education or social care records;
qualitative data where participants may be identifiable;
geospatial data that could reveal sensitive locations;
data subject to commercial licence or data provider agreements;
Indigenous, community-controlled or culturally sensitive data;
data involving children or vulnerable groups.

For these projects, the DMP should be explicit about:

access controls;
de-identification or pseudonymisation;
linkage and separation of identifiers;
secure transfer;
approved storage environments;
retention and destruction;
review of outputs before release;
what happens at the end of the project;
who has authority to approve sharing.

What assessors and reviewers look for
When DMPs are reviewed by funders, institutions, supervisors or collaborators, the strongest plans are usually:

specific rather than generic;
proportionate to project risk;
realistic about staffing and resources;
explicit about sensitive data and constraints;
clear about who is responsible;
clear about what will be shared and what will not;
connected to FAIR principles;
updated when circumstances change.

A DMP does not need to be long to be good. It needs to be clear, truthful and usable.

Learning objectives
By the end of this chapter, you should be able to:

explain why messy data make analysis fragile;
recognise common spreadsheet and data-entry risks;
describe the core principles of tidy data;
distinguish raw, cleaned and analysis-ready data without repeating the full project-organisation chapter;
document missingness, exclusions and filtering decisions;
identify minimum checks that should be carried out before analysis;
create or improve a simple data dictionary/codebook.







Boundary with other chapters



This chapter is not mainly about folder structures or file naming. Those are covered in Chapter 3. It is also not mainly about governance, storage or access. Those are covered in Chapter 4.
Here, the question is simpler: is the dataset itself structured so that it can be understood, checked and analysed safely?

If the data are messy, everything is fragile
Messy data make research harder to check, rerun, defend and reuse. Problems that look small during data entry can become substantial later, especially when data are linked, cleaned, merged or analysed by someone else.
Common consequences include:

analysing the wrong version of a dataset;
treating missing values as real values;
mixing text and numeric values in the same column;
losing information that was stored only in formatting or comments;
introducing manual corrections that cannot be reproduced;
making code more complicated than it needs to be.

Data Carpentry emphasises that small changes in spreadsheet formatting can improve efficiency and reliability when data are later cleaned and analysed1.

Quick reflection
Have you ever analysed, cleaned or shared the wrong version of a dataset?
If so, what made the error possible?

unclear filename;
mixed raw and cleaned data;
missing documentation;
manual edits;
several versions stored in different places;
no clear owner or approval point.

Spreadsheet risks
Spreadsheets are useful for viewing, checking and small-scale data entry. They are also risky when they become the main place where cleaning, coding, analysis and documentation happen invisibly.
Common risks include:

mixed data types: numbers, dates and text in the same column;
hidden formatting: colours, font styles or cell comments used to convey meaning;
manual edits: changes made by hand without a script or log;
implicit missing values: blanks, NA, N/A, 0, -999 or text used inconsistently;
merged cells: useful for visual display but difficult for analysis software;
multiple tables in one sheet: visually convenient but machine-unfriendly;
multiple tabs with inconsistent structures: hard to combine and check later;
dates automatically changed by software.







Spreadsheet rule of thumb



Use spreadsheets for inspection and controlled data entry where appropriate. Avoid using formatting, colours, comments or manual edits as the only record of information that matters for analysis.

Missing data and exclusions
Missing data are not just a technical nuisance. They can change the interpretation of results, the analytic sample and the conclusions.
Good practice includes:

using explicit and consistent missing-value codes;
distinguishing true zero from missing or not applicable;
documenting why data are missing when known;
recording exclusions and filtering decisions;
reporting how missingness was handled in analysis.

Kang describes missing data as a problem that requires attention to the pattern and mechanism of missingness, as well as the method used to handle it5. For this workshop, the main message is practical: do not let missingness become invisible.






Missing values need definitions



A blank cell, 0, NA, N/A, -999, unknown and not applicable do not mean the same thing unless you define them.
In R, NA is often appropriate for missing values. In a shared dataset or spreadsheet, the meaning of any missing-value code should be stated in the data dictionary.

Learning objectives
By the end of this chapter, you should be able to:

explain why documentation is central to reproducibility, continuity and handover;
distinguish between different documentation artefacts and their purposes;
decide when to use a README, codebook, metadata record, decision log, changelog, ELN, SOP or protocol;
recognise documentation as a way of reducing project risk and “bus factor”;
apply proportionate documentation practices in everyday research workflows.

Why documentation matters
Documentation is often treated as an administrative extra. In reproducible research, it is part of the research method. It provides evidence of how choices were made and helps others understand whether those choices are justified.
A common problem is not simply that researchers document too little. It is that documentation has no clear purpose. Some projects have almost nothing written down; others have information scattered across emails, Teams chats, notebooks, Word documents, old protocols and people’s memories. Both situations are fragile.






Under-documenting and over-documenting are both risks



Documentation is useful when it is findable, current and purposeful. It is less useful when it is either missing or spread across too many places without a clear owner.


Good documentation helps to:

track what happened;
make decisions visible;
support new team members;
reduce reliance on memory;
make handover easier;
support audit, peer review and reuse;
explain deviations, exclusions and constraints.

The Turing Way and Good Enough Practices both emphasise that documentation should make it possible for someone else — or your future self — to reconstruct the work, not simply remember that something was done1,2.

The bus factor
The bus factor is a useful way to think about documentation. It asks: how many people would need to become unavailable before the project could no longer continue?
In research projects, the problem is often less dramatic than a bus: a student finishes, a research fellow moves institution, a collaborator changes role, or a data manager is on leave. The effect is the same if key knowledge only exists in one person’s head.

Activity: what would you need to know?
Imagine that a key member of your project team becomes unavailable tomorrow.
What would you need to know?
Consider:

where the data are stored;
who has access;
which files are raw, derived or final;
what approvals or data-sharing agreements apply;
how exclusions or analysis decisions were made;
what software, packages and versions were used;
which outputs are current;
what still needs to be done.

Documentation should be proportionate
Not every project needs every type of document. A short student project may need a README, a data dictionary and a few notes on analysis decisions. A multi-partner project using sensitive linked data may need a DMP, README, data dictionary, metadata record, decision log, changelog, SOPs, governance documents and access-control records.
The principle is proportionality:

document decisions that affect interpretation, reuse or trust;
keep documentation close to the relevant files;
avoid duplicating the same information in multiple places;
make ownership and update frequency clear;
use simple formats where possible.

Data dictionaries and codebooks
A data dictionary or codebook describes the variables in a dataset. This is different from a README. A README orientates the project or dataset as a whole; a data dictionary explains the internal structure of the data.
A useful data dictionary includes:

variable name;
clear variable description;
unit of measurement;
expected data type;
allowed values or categories;
coding scheme;
missing-value codes;
source variable or source dataset;
derivation or transformation, where relevant.

This is particularly important for administrative, survey, cohort and linked datasets, where variable meanings may depend on coding rules, collection context, eligibility, geography, time period or provider systems5,6.

Metadata: dataset-level context
Metadata describe the dataset as a research object. They support discovery, citation, interpretation, archiving and reuse.
At minimum, metadata should capture:

title and description;
creators and contributors;
data source and collection context;
dates, versions and time period covered;
geography or population, where relevant;
inclusion and exclusion criteria;
provenance: how the data were generated, processed or cleaned;
access conditions and restrictions;
licence or reuse conditions;
persistent identifier, if available.

Metadata standards vary by field and repository. Examples include Dublin Core, DataCite, DDI, SDMX and ISO 19115 for geographic information7–11. The Research Data Alliance Metadata Standards Catalog can help identify relevant standards12. In practice, most researchers do not need to master these standards, but they do need to understand what metadata are trying to achieve: enough context for the data to be found, understood and reused appropriately13,14.






Metadata is not only for open data



Restricted or sensitive data still need metadata. Even when the data themselves cannot be shared openly, metadata can explain what exists, who controls access, what restrictions apply, and how legitimate access requests are handled.

Changelogs
A changelog records what changed. It is most useful for documents, datasets, code outputs, protocols and resources that evolve over time.
A simple changelog should record:

version number or date;
what changed;
why it changed;
who made the change;
whether earlier outputs are affected.

For manuscripts or governance documents, the changelog may be part of a document control table. For code or data outputs, it may sit in a CHANGELOG.md file. For more technical projects, Git can provide a detailed history, but a short human-readable changelog is still useful for major changes15.

Electronic lab notebooks
Electronic Lab Notebooks (ELNs) provide a chronological record of work. They are common in laboratory settings but can also be useful for computational, qualitative and data-intensive research.
ELNs can help record:

what was attempted;
what happened;
unexpected problems;
decisions made during active work;
deviations from protocols;
links to files, outputs or scripts;
reflections on what to try next.

The Turing Way notes that ELNs can improve searchability, remote access, secure storage and sharing compared with traditional paper notebooks16. They are not, however, a replacement for all documentation. A project may still need a README, data dictionary, SOPs and formal governance records.






Avoid the “everything notebook” problem



ELNs are good for chronological work records. They are less good as the only place to store final instructions, data dictionaries, access rules or project orientation.

SOPs: documenting repeatable tasks
A Standard Operating Procedure is a set of step-by-step instructions for carrying out a routine task. SOPs are useful when a task needs to be done consistently across people, time or sites.
SOPs are most useful when:

the task is repeated;
inconsistency would affect data quality;
new people need training;
there are safety, governance or compliance implications;
the task involves multiple steps or decisions.

Hollmann and colleagues describe SOPs as tools for reducing deviations and maintaining consistent quality in research workflows17. For this workshop, the practical point is simple: write an SOP when a task needs to be done the same way more than once.
A good SOP should include:

title and purpose;
scope: when it applies and when it does not;
responsibilities;
required materials/software/access;
step-by-step procedure;
quality checks;
safety or governance considerations;
version, date and author;
review date.


Activity: the cup of tea protocol
Write a step-by-step protocol for making a cup of tea. You have three minutes.
Then compare protocols. Did everyone specify:

type and brand of tea?
cup, mug or teapot?
water source?
water temperature?
brewing time?
milk first or last?
how to judge when it is “done”?

This activity shows how expert knowledge can hide assumptions. The same problem occurs in research methods.

Protocols, preregistration and reporting guidelines
Protocols and preregistrations are a special form of documentation. They make planned methods and analyses visible before results are known. They can help distinguish planned analyses from exploratory analyses, but they should not be treated as a prison. Deviations can be legitimate if they are documented transparently19,20.
Preregistration and protocol registration may be useful for:

clinical trials;
intervention studies;
systematic reviews;
planned secondary data analyses;
studies where analytic flexibility could affect interpretation.

Common platforms include OSF Registries, PROSPERO and protocols.io21–23. For systematic reviews, the Cochrane Handbook provides guidance on protocol development and review methods24. There are also templates specifically designed for secondary data analysis25.






Protocols can change



The value of a protocol is not that nothing changes. The value is that changes are visible, justified and interpretable.


Reporting guidelines are another form of transparency support. They help researchers report studies with enough detail for readers to understand what was done. EQUATOR curates reporting guidelines across study designs, including CONSORT, SPIRIT, STROBE, PRISMA, MOOSE and STARD26.
Reporting guidelines should usually be considered early, not only at manuscript submission.

Activity: how could you show your working?
Imagine you are contacted about a paper you published two years ago because a similar paper has reported contradictory results.
What could you provide to show your working?
Consider:

project README;
data dictionary or codebook;
metadata;
analysis scripts;
decision log;
changelog;
environment notes;
protocol or preregistration;
reporting guideline checklist;
data access statement;
repository or DOI;
documented deviations or sensitivity analyses.


Reflection
Choose one current project. What is the single piece of documentation that would most improve its reproducibility or handover?
Write one action you could take this week.

Learning objectives
By the end of this chapter, you should be able to:

explain why code quality is part of research quality;
recognise features of readable, reusable, and defensible research code;
use simple checks to catch errors early;
understand how versioning supports traceability and safe change;
identify where light automation can reduce manual work and improve reproducibility;
describe how sustainable computing relates to reproducible coding practice.

This chapter builds on Chapter 5 — Organising and tidying data and Chapter 6 — Documentation, ELNs and SOPs. Check on [Resources — code example] for an example on how to write good code. It prepares for the later chapter on publishing, persistent identifiers, licensing and preparing outputs for reuse.

Code quality is research quality
In research, code quality is not mainly about elegance. It is about trust.
Good research code should be:

readable — another person can follow the logic;
explicit — assumptions, inputs, outputs, and parameters are visible;
robust — errors are caught early;
re-runnable — the same inputs produce the same outputs;
traceable — changes can be understood and recovered.

Poor code creates research risk. It can hide errors, make analyses difficult to rerun, and make it unclear how results were produced. In some cases, poor code can make a study effectively irreproducible, even when the data and scripts are technically available.
Good-enough code is therefore not a technical luxury. It is part of defensible research practice.






Key idea



Code quality is not about writing beautiful code for its own sake. It is about making the analytical route visible enough that results can be checked, explained and rerun.

Avoid copy-and-paste code
Copy-and-paste code is a common source of errors. If the same code appears several times with small changes, it becomes easy to update one version but forget another.
A better approach is to write a small function.
For example, instead of repeating similar plotting code for different variables, define one function:
make_pm25_boxplot &lt;- function(data, x_var, x_label, panel_label, x_labels = NULL) {

  plot_object &lt;- ggplot2::ggplot(
    data = data,
    ggplot2::aes(
      x = .data[[x_var]],
      y = pm25,
      fill = factor(year)
    )
  ) +
    ggplot2::geom_boxplot() +
    ggplot2::labs(
      title = panel_label,
      x = x_label,
      y = "Annual mean PM2.5 concentration (µg/m³)"
    ) +
    ggplot2::facet_wrap(~ year, nrow = 1)

  if (!is.null(x_labels)) {
    plot_object &lt;- plot_object + ggplot2::scale_x_discrete(labels = x_labels)
  }

  return(plot_object)
}
This improves:

readability;
consistency;
maintainability;
ease of updating plots;
reproducibility of figures.

A function should usually do one task, have clear inputs, and return a clear output.

Make dependencies explicit
A reproducible script should make clear what it needs before it can run.
This includes:

required packages;
required input files;
expected variables;
relevant software versions;
external tools or data sources.

For teaching, it can be useful to include a helper function that installs missing packages:
load_or_install &lt;- function(packages) {
  missing_packages &lt;- packages[!packages %in% installed.packages()[, "Package"]]

  if (length(missing_packages) &gt; 0) {
    install.packages(missing_packages)
  }

  invisible(lapply(packages, library, character.only = TRUE))
}
However, package installation inside scripts is not the strongest long-term reproducibility strategy. For research projects, tools such as renv in R provide a more robust way to record package versions and recreate the software environment.
At minimum, record the packages and versions used:
sessionInfo()
or, if using renv:
renv::snapshot()






Teaching example versus research workflow



Installing packages automatically inside a teaching script can help learners get started. For a research project, recording the exact package versions is more reproducible than simply installing the latest versions.

Build in checks as you go
Good code anticipates failure.
Useful checks include:

expected number of rows or columns;
whether identifiers are unique;
whether categories contain unexpected values;
whether values fall within plausible ranges;
whether joins have created missing or duplicated records;
whether outputs have been saved successfully.

For example:
if (any(is.na(nursery_pm25_data$uprn))) {
  stop("Missing UPRNs detected after linkage.")
}
or:
if (any(nursery_pm25_data$pm25 &lt; 0, na.rm = TRUE)) {
  stop("Negative PM2.5 values detected. Check exposure data.")
}
These checks are simple, but they can prevent long chains of downstream error.






Basic checks are not trivial



Checking that files, variables, rows, identifiers and values are as expected may feel simple, but these checks catch many common causes of irreproducible or incorrect analysis.

Testing supports safe change
Research code often changes. You may clean it, simplify it, adapt it to new data, or reuse it in a new project.
This process is safer when tests are in place.
Tests help you check whether:

outputs still make sense after changing code;
refactoring has not broken the analysis;
new data extracts still meet the expected structure;
assumptions remain valid.

Formal testing frameworks are useful in larger projects. In R, the testthat package is commonly used, and the testing chapter in R Packages is a good introduction.
For many research projects, however, the first step is simply to include lightweight checks in scripts and reports. These checks are often enough to catch the most common problems.

Light automation: make repetition reliable
Automation does not need to mean complex pipelines.
In this chapter, automation means making repeated work runnable without manual copying, clicking, or editing.
Examples include:

running a script from start to finish;
knitting an R Markdown or Quarto report;
regenerating a table from source data;
regenerating a figure from source data;
saving outputs to predictable folders;
using a function instead of repeating similar code.

The example R Markdown file demonstrates light automation because one action — knitting the report — can:

load packages;
check inputs;
read data;
validate assumptions;
create a summary table;
create figures;
save outputs.

This is already a reproducible workflow.
More advanced tools such as targets, Make, or Snakemake can be introduced later for larger projects, but they are not required to benefit from automation.
The principle is simple: automate one repeated thing first.

What not to over-automate
Automation is most useful for repeated and stable tasks.
Good candidates include:

data validation checks;
missingness summaries;
repeated tables;
repeated figures;
standard reports;
routine data refreshes.

Do not over-automate early exploratory thinking.
Leave flexibility for:

trying different visualisations;
understanding unusual data patterns;
refining variables;
developing hypotheses;
changing analytical strategy.

A good compromise is to keep exploratory scripts, but avoid manual changes that cannot be traced. Exploration should be flexible, but not invisible.

AI-generated code
AI-generated code should be treated like any other external contribution.
It may be useful, but it still needs to be:

read and understood;
checked against the data;
tested with expected and unexpected inputs;
documented;
adapted to the project context;
reviewed for errors, bias, and inappropriate assumptions.

Do not include code in an analysis simply because it runs. Running is not the same as being correct.

Learning objectives
By the end of this chapter, you should be able to:

understand publishing as the release of research outputs, not only papers;
identify which outputs from a project could be shared, archived or described;
explain how persistent identifiers support credit, linkage and traceability;
distinguish access decisions from licensing decisions;
prepare data, code, documentation and other outputs for responsible reuse;
recognise how publishing choices affect reproducibility, sustainability and long-term value.

This chapter builds on Chapter 2 — FAIR basics, Chapter 4 — Data Management Plans, Chapter 6 — Documentation and protocols, and Chapter 7 — Coding for reproducible research.

Publishing beyond the paper
Research outputs extend beyond journal articles. They may include:

datasets and metadata;
analysis code and workflows;
protocols, preregistrations and documentation;
computational notebooks and reports;
figures, tables and derived materials;
preprints and accepted manuscripts;
software, packages or apps;
training materials and reusable templates.

Publishing these outputs supports transparency, enables reuse, and ensures appropriate attribution. However, different outputs require different access routes, licences, documentation and preservation strategies.






Key point



Publishing does not mean uploading everything to a website. It means making deliberate decisions about what is released, where it is preserved, how it is described, who can access it, and how it should be cited.

Publishing as release management
It is useful to think of publishing as creating a release of a research object.
A release usually involves:

deciding what is in scope;
freezing a version;
documenting what the release contains;
describing known limitations;
assigning or recording a persistent identifier;
specifying access conditions;
applying an appropriate licence;
linking related outputs, such as data, code and publications.

Thinking in terms of releases is particularly helpful when outputs evolve over time. For example, code may continue to change after a paper is submitted, or a dataset may be updated after new linkage or cleaning. A release marks the version that supports a specific output, paper or decision.






Practical habit



Before submission, create a checklist of the exact data, code, documentation and outputs that support the paper. This helps avoid the common problem where the published article is linked to a moving or unclear version of the underlying materials.

Sharing is not the same as enabling reuse
Sharing means making something available.
Enabling reuse requires more than access. It requires enough context for someone else to understand what the output is, how it was produced, what restrictions apply, and how it can be used appropriately.
A reusable output usually needs:

a clear title and description;
authorship and contributor information;
date and version;
relationship to other outputs;
metadata;
methods or provenance information;
file format information;
access conditions;
licence;
citation instructions;
contact or support route where appropriate.

You can upload a dataset and still make it unusable. Without context, documentation and licensing, others may not be able to interpret it, cite it or reuse it responsibly.

Persistent identifiers
Persistent identifiers provide stable references to research outputs, people and organisations. They help link outputs across systems and reduce reliance on unstable URLs.
Common examples include:


DOI
A Digital Object Identifier is a persistent identifier for research outputs such as articles, datasets, code releases, preprints, protocols and reports.


ORCID iD
An ORCID iD is a persistent identifier for a researcher. It helps link outputs to a person despite name changes, name variants or institutional moves.


ROR ID
A Research Organization Registry identifier is a persistent identifier for a research organisation. UCL, for example, has a ROR ID.


Persistent identifiers support:

discovery;
citation;
credit;
attribution;
version tracking;
linking datasets, code, papers and protocols;
reporting for institutions, funders and research assessment.


DOI is not just a link
A DOI is more than a convenient URL. It is a stable identifier supported by metadata. The DOI should resolve to a landing page that describes the object, provides access information and gives citation details.
For datasets and code, the landing page is often as important as the file itself because it records title, creators, version, licence, funder, related outputs and access conditions.

Data and code availability statements
Many journals now require data and code availability statements. These statements should explain what is available, where it can be found, and what restrictions apply.
A weak statement says only:

Data are available on request.

A stronger statement explains:

what data exist;
whether they can be shared;
where metadata are available;
whether code is available;
what repository or DOI applies;
what restrictions apply and why;
who can request access;
what approval or data-sharing agreement is required.

Examples:
The analysis code supporting this study is available at [repository/DOI]. The individual-level linked administrative data cannot be made openly available because they are subject to data-provider agreements and information governance restrictions. Metadata and variable descriptions are available at [repository/DOI]. Access requests should be directed to [data provider/institutional route].
The dataset and code supporting this analysis are available in the UCL Research Data Repository at [DOI] under a CC BY 4.0 licence. The repository record includes the README, data dictionary and analysis scripts required to reproduce the tables and figures.
Availability statements are part of the reuse package. They should be written early enough that restrictions are understood before submission.

Preprints as early dissemination
Preprints are public versions of research outputs shared before formal peer review. They support early dissemination, transparency and feedback, and are now widely used in many areas of health, population and computational research.
Preprints can:

make findings visible earlier;
establish precedence and credit;
invite methodological and substantive feedback;
allow sharing when journal publication is delayed.

However, preprints:

have not undergone peer review;
may change substantially before publication;
should be interpreted with caution, especially for policy- or clinically relevant findings;
may be subject to journal, funder or institutional expectations.

Good practice includes clearly labelling outputs as preprints, linking to subsequent accepted or published versions where available, and avoiding overstatement of findings.
Preprints are part of the publishing lifecycle, not a replacement for peer review.

Reporting guidelines and transparency
Reporting guidelines help ensure that publications include the minimum information needed for interpretation, appraisal and reuse. They do not replace good study design or reproducible workflows, but they improve the completeness and transparency of reporting.
Examples include:

CONSORT for randomised trials;
SPIRIT for trial protocols;
STROBE for observational studies;
PRISMA for systematic reviews and meta-analyses;
STARD for diagnostic accuracy studies;
MOOSE for meta-analyses of observational studies.

The EQUATOR Network curates reporting guidelines across study designs and disciplines.
Reporting guidelines fit here because they are part of preparing outputs for publication. They should be considered alongside repository deposits, availability statements, licences and metadata.

Software and code citation
Code is a research output. It should be cited when it supports a publication or is reused by others.
Good practice includes:

creating a release of the code used for the paper;
depositing or archiving the release in a repository that issues a DOI;
including a citation file, such as CITATION.cff, where appropriate;
documenting dependencies and software versions;
linking the code release to the paper and related datasets.

GitHub alone is useful for collaboration, but it is not the same as a preserved release. For citation and archiving, GitHub releases can be connected to repositories such as Zenodo to mint DOIs for specific versions.

Computational notebooks
Jupyter, R Markdown and Quarto notebooks can be useful research objects. To make them reusable, consider:

whether the notebook runs from top to bottom;
whether outputs are embedded or regenerated;
whether data dependencies are clear;
whether the computational environment is recorded;
whether the notebook is deposited with sufficient metadata;
whether outputs are versioned and citable.

A notebook that only works on the author’s computer is not yet a reusable research object.

Discontinuing or maintaining software
Not all research software will be maintained indefinitely. This is normal, but it should be communicated clearly.
If software or code will no longer be maintained, consider:

archiving the final release;
stating that active development has ended;
documenting known limitations;
identifying dependencies and last-tested versions;
linking to successor tools where available;
preserving the code with a DOI if it supports published findings.

This is part of responsible reuse. Users should not have to guess whether a tool is maintained, deprecated or unsafe to use.

Context is part of the output
Reuse depends on context.
Good publishing practice includes documenting:

analytical assumptions and decisions;
known limitations and sources of uncertainty;
constraints on interpretation or reuse;
relationships between outputs;
provenance;
file formats and software dependencies;
access routes and restrictions.

This includes structured metadata that supports discovery and interpretation, even when access to the underlying data is restricted.






Metadata can often be open when data cannot



For sensitive or restricted data, an open metadata record can still support discovery, citation and transparency without exposing confidential data.

Sustainability and publishing
Well-prepared outputs reduce downstream burden.
Clear documentation, stable releases and archived outputs:

reduce repeated clarification requests;
avoid unnecessary recomputation;
support long-term reuse without ongoing effort;
reduce the risk of abandoned or unusable outputs;
make outputs easier to cite and credit.

Publishing is therefore part of sustainable research practice. Choices about what to publish, how to document it and where to archive it directly affect reproducibility and long-term value.

